17
00:00:48,886 --> 00:01:01,009
I sent some feedback from two school committee members, and I just sent the third earlier just before the meeting.

18
00:01:02,670 --> 00:01:06,911
The feedback, one was from Erin DiBenedetto.

19
00:01:07,951 --> 00:01:10,352
And let me just quickly bring it up.

20
00:01:13,248 --> 00:01:25,079
Erin wrote just for the, I know that the committee members have seen it, but for everybody else, she says, I think four years is preferred, but that may be too long, so at least three.

21
00:01:25,739 --> 00:01:27,761
Running every two years is just too much.

22
00:01:28,442 --> 00:01:32,485
And again, Erin was on the school committee and experienced that running every two years.

23
00:01:33,606 --> 00:01:36,689
Four years is a long time, so it may be too daunting for some.

24
00:01:38,416 --> 00:01:50,999
On question number three, and this was about wards or at large, she says, I like wards for city council, and I think that having each part of the city represented at school committee would be beneficial.

25
00:01:51,759 --> 00:01:56,760
I also like that when you were elected, you represent all students of Medford, not just your ward.

26
00:01:59,561 --> 00:02:02,202
She favors the mayor being the chair of the school committee.

27
00:02:05,971 --> 00:02:12,336
And she does not favor term limits because she thinks that knowledge and the history, knowing the history is helpful.

28
00:02:13,577 --> 00:02:14,578
So that was errands.

29
00:02:15,558 --> 00:02:19,061
Then from Cheryl Rodriguez, who was a candidate for school committee.

30
00:02:21,628 --> 00:02:24,051
She said that she thinks two is fine.

31
00:02:25,712 --> 00:02:27,394
I think the committee should change.

32
00:02:27,715 --> 00:02:36,384
People should yield to others and not park forever, but it should match city council to not necessitate extra elections.

33
00:02:37,265 --> 00:02:40,248
A school committee only election would yield very low turnout.

34
00:02:41,686 --> 00:02:50,193
She says a four-year term would not have prevented her from running, but it is a danger of when supermajorities exist on the committee as it does now.

35
00:02:50,713 --> 00:02:51,914
And again, these are her words.

36
00:02:52,435 --> 00:02:55,537
There is the issue of preventing parents and students from being heard.

37
00:02:56,278 --> 00:02:59,200
One voice all voting the same on any agenda item.

38
00:03:02,522 --> 00:03:15,814
For question number three, which was about the wards versus at large, wards may lessen the, and she quotes, we have to all vote to appease the one school that has the largest amount of voters living in its boundaries, end quotes.

39
00:03:16,455 --> 00:03:18,036
Other schools deserve a voice too.

40
00:03:18,817 --> 00:03:23,061
Far too long, that has largely been impossible because those that vote get the most attention.

41
00:03:26,779 --> 00:03:36,726
She says that having the mayor be the chair works in that you are more likely to get a response from the mayor's office regardless of your political views.

42
00:03:37,487 --> 00:03:44,451
Today, we have a one-group voice school committee for the most part, and any who don't agree find their concerns in emails ignored.

43
00:03:46,453 --> 00:03:47,954
She does believe in term limits.

44
00:03:50,556 --> 00:03:56,999
says children come and go from the school system, being aware of the goings on in the schools is vital for a successful committee.

45
00:03:58,420 --> 00:04:03,863
She also mentions that it would also be nice if their public participation policy was deemed to be unacceptable.

46
00:04:04,683 --> 00:04:12,647
Going through the hurdles to be heard and then speaking to people who won't respond to you has led to the public feeling they are not welcome at the school committee.

47
00:04:13,527 --> 00:04:15,888
My 15-year-old daughter said, why bother?

48
00:04:15,988 --> 00:04:18,950
I doubt they are even listening if they won't talk back to you.

49
00:04:20,047 --> 00:04:23,449
Thanks to the group for undertaking this labor, Cheryl Rodriguez.

50
00:04:24,569 --> 00:04:33,894
And then the one that just came in for Kathy is, she says she's enjoying her retirement.

51
00:04:35,014 --> 00:04:37,776
She thinks two to three years would be preferable.

52
00:04:39,497 --> 00:04:44,799
She's not sure whether the four years would have been daunting for her starting out.

53
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:48,081
She favors an at-large school committee.

54
00:04:49,446 --> 00:04:52,408
And she favors the mayor being the chair of the committee.

55
00:04:53,729 --> 00:04:55,249
She does not favor term limits.

56
00:04:55,930 --> 00:04:57,211
Let the people vote, she says.

57
00:04:57,891 --> 00:05:05,255
So that's the feedback which we received so far from other people we've reached out to.

58
00:05:05,275 --> 00:05:07,036
Okay.

59
00:05:09,257 --> 00:05:10,038
Any other questions?

60
00:05:11,769 --> 00:05:13,390
On that note, pretty straightforward.

61
00:05:13,550 --> 00:05:16,893
Okay, so I don't see that Aubrey has come.

62
00:05:17,693 --> 00:05:23,097
Ron, are you able to share the Collins Center Article 4?

63
00:05:23,177 --> 00:05:23,377
Yes.

64
00:05:35,980 --> 00:05:44,852
Now, I believe that some of you and maybe Ron, in particular, and Eunice, you went through this process with another part while I have not.

65
00:05:46,093 --> 00:05:52,922
So I'm not quite sure how you attacked it specifically because we haven't really come up with a final

66
00:05:55,130 --> 00:06:01,473
we haven't resolved the whole issue before us about which way should we check.

67
00:06:02,194 --> 00:06:17,722
I did wonder, as we start this process, one of the things which happened since our past meeting was that a school committee member, Melanie McLaughlin, has decided to withdraw from the school committee.

68
00:06:18,622 --> 00:06:19,783
So a major change.

69
00:06:20,023 --> 00:06:23,345
And what's really interesting about that is that leaves only one

70
00:06:24,225 --> 00:06:28,808
a person behind her, John Intapa, in line.

71
00:06:29,989 --> 00:06:42,797
And when I thought about this a lot this week, because I kept on saying to myself, okay, so what happens if we're trying to pull from eight wards and get everybody have their own, you know, school committee representation?

72
00:06:43,878 --> 00:06:45,359
And what happens

73
00:06:46,864 --> 00:06:54,136
You know, as I've mentioned before, it's not, I mean, there were times we had a lot of people running, but there were times when we did not.

74
00:06:55,859 --> 00:06:59,705
And there was one time when we had,

75
00:07:00,710 --> 00:07:02,012
None of the seats were contested.

76
00:07:02,072 --> 00:07:03,413
Nobody ran it against us.

77
00:07:03,994 --> 00:07:06,977
And many times when there were there were only two or three candidates.

78
00:07:07,598 --> 00:07:12,003
And in this particular case, there was only one one candidate.

79
00:07:12,384 --> 00:07:15,748
Now, thankfully, John won.

80
00:07:15,888 --> 00:07:20,213
I'm assuming and maybe somebody already knows that John will take the seat.

81
00:07:21,905 --> 00:07:23,686
I don't know anything about that.

82
00:07:23,726 --> 00:07:24,107
I don't know.

83
00:07:24,207 --> 00:07:25,728
Please accept it or not accepted.

84
00:07:26,789 --> 00:07:27,809
I haven't heard anything.

85
00:07:28,049 --> 00:07:30,911
I have a little bit of information on that.

86
00:07:32,112 --> 00:07:33,814
My understanding is that.

87
00:07:36,411 --> 00:07:40,595
I guess they have spoken to him about taking the seat and he's interested.

88
00:07:41,155 --> 00:07:43,657
He was in chambers last night.

89
00:07:45,459 --> 00:08:00,052
What I thought was interesting, both in a meeting that they had last week and last night's meeting is that they call member McLaughlin's name and marker is absent, even though her resignation had taken place a week ago too.

90
00:08:01,326 --> 00:08:02,266
Yeah, we could go today.

91
00:08:02,286 --> 00:08:04,967
So I don't know why that's happening.

92
00:08:05,048 --> 00:08:07,388
But John was in the audience last night.

93
00:08:08,349 --> 00:08:29,898
And I'm not sure if they haven't been able to work out a swearing in time or some other things that Erica Reinfeld, who is one of the sitting school committee members, mentioned on a post on the Medford Reddit forum, which is kind of similar to

94
00:08:30,813 --> 00:08:48,552
Facebook, like the Medford Politics Forum, if you're familiar, is that because our charter does not have a provision for a vacancy on school committee, what to do with a vacancy on school committee, it does for city council.

95
00:08:49,233 --> 00:08:50,935
If you read our four-page charter,

96
00:08:52,616 --> 00:08:59,663
If there's a vacancy on city council, it tells us exactly what we need to do, but there is no provision for a vacancy on school committee.

97
00:09:00,103 --> 00:09:04,307
I can tell you what the past practice was, because it has happened before.

98
00:09:05,308 --> 00:09:11,813
And as you and I discussed, Eunice, we think it happened prior to any of the research you did, which is why it didn't come up.

99
00:09:13,435 --> 00:09:15,236
And it would Tom Frieda,

100
00:09:16,138 --> 00:09:18,879
was the committee member, if I recall.

101
00:09:20,140 --> 00:09:23,682
I think he withdrew and Nolan came in.

102
00:09:23,762 --> 00:09:26,923
I'm a little sketchy of my memory.

103
00:09:27,264 --> 00:09:28,724
I'd have to go back and take a look.

104
00:09:29,205 --> 00:09:35,148
But without any question, whichever way it went, the person who was next in line then took the seat.

105
00:09:36,748 --> 00:09:38,489
So that is my expectation.

106
00:09:38,689 --> 00:09:55,114
But it certainly calls to mind as we're trying to work through this process, it certainly underlines to us how carefully we need to make sure that we're trying to anticipate potential vacancies.

107
00:09:55,194 --> 00:10:02,836
But also, as we're trying to make this very difficult suggestion about which way

108
00:10:03,776 --> 00:10:15,642
we should write our opinions about at-large ward and the other things that are affected by it.

109
00:10:16,042 --> 00:10:17,323
It's kind of interesting.

110
00:10:17,783 --> 00:10:19,284
I mean, you know.

111
00:10:19,304 --> 00:10:20,324
Here we are.

112
00:10:20,925 --> 00:10:28,909
It was interesting to read through article four where we have the different towns and cities and how their school committee is

113
00:10:30,822 --> 00:10:33,803
set up, how it's elected, what happens when things go through.

114
00:10:34,983 --> 00:10:47,967
It was very interesting to read, and I am a bit surprised, though, that we do not have anything in process to replace a seat vacated on any committee in our city, especially school committees.

115
00:10:48,207 --> 00:10:49,387
I know.

116
00:10:50,408 --> 00:10:52,568
That's why we're doing this.

117
00:10:52,748 --> 00:10:55,649
I can still state that, yeah, well, this is the thing.

118
00:10:55,969 --> 00:10:58,270
This is why this absolutely needs to be done.

119
00:10:59,638 --> 00:11:03,002
Remember, too, we also default to the Massachusetts state general laws, too.

120
00:11:03,062 --> 00:11:05,225
So I'm sure somewhere in there is that law.

121
00:11:05,265 --> 00:11:10,271
That's why the importance of what we do is written down so that it's noted.

122
00:11:10,391 --> 00:11:14,616
And just to your, I detect concern from Paulette about

123
00:11:15,737 --> 00:11:19,321
the ability to find candidates at-large versus ward.

124
00:11:19,881 --> 00:11:27,267
And all I can say is that we did a at-large election with the school committee, and we're down to nobody on the bench now.

125
00:11:27,367 --> 00:11:34,814
So the fact that we don't have candidates is a separate problem, in my mind.

126
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:43,531
I think also, though, I think that we don't have a lot of candidates, whether it be Ward or at-large, because a lot of people aren't interested in running.

127
00:11:44,152 --> 00:11:46,012
That's what I'm saying.

128
00:11:46,092 --> 00:11:50,254
It's not necessarily because we're at-large versus Ward.

129
00:11:50,274 --> 00:11:51,315
I think it's the same.

130
00:11:51,335 --> 00:11:56,277
And I will, just to continue the thought, tell you that it would be easier

131
00:11:57,417 --> 00:12:01,460
to replace a school committee person if we were in ward representation.

132
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:05,623
That would mean you just get that ward together to pick a representative.

133
00:12:06,063 --> 00:12:15,490
So cost-wise and process-wise would be quicker than if we had to go at a full city election to replace them.

134
00:12:16,071 --> 00:12:16,751
Right.

135
00:12:16,831 --> 00:12:20,814
Rod, counter to that, and I am going to challenge you on this.

136
00:12:20,854 --> 00:12:21,074
Sure.

137
00:12:22,195 --> 00:12:26,717
Because counter to that is, maybe it'll be easier.

138
00:12:27,177 --> 00:12:32,960
But what if there's really someone who's interested in education in Ward 2?

139
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:37,542
And they can't run because there's somebody else sitting in the seat.

140
00:12:39,283 --> 00:12:41,064
But you have to convince somebody.

141
00:12:41,584 --> 00:12:43,065
We would have an at-large spot.

142
00:12:43,725 --> 00:12:46,927
We would have to look, possibly, at at-large spots.

143
00:12:48,567 --> 00:12:50,688
And then the question is the size of the committee.

144
00:12:51,209 --> 00:12:51,469
Correct.

145
00:12:53,162 --> 00:12:58,385
And the question there is how effective it's going to be.

146
00:12:58,685 --> 00:13:03,868
As you increase, here I'm speaking from experience.

147
00:13:04,008 --> 00:13:11,833
I mean, I'm not saying that our current seven is optimum.

148
00:13:12,673 --> 00:13:16,095
And you might convince me in trying

149
00:13:20,327 --> 00:13:27,374
to get more people from a greater spread in Medford to up it.

150
00:13:29,255 --> 00:13:37,123
But I just see it as, I don't know what the optimum size is.

151
00:13:38,005 --> 00:13:46,127
And unfortunately, it's our task to make that decision to represent our recommendations to the committee of the whole, so.

152
00:13:46,387 --> 00:13:46,587
Right.

153
00:13:46,667 --> 00:13:57,330
So the question is maybe kind of wondering where, you know, where we are in agreement and where we are in disagreement.

154
00:13:57,390 --> 00:14:02,652
I think, you know, after I went through these past two

155
00:14:04,211 --> 00:14:21,890
this past two weeks and thinking about Melanie leaving and what that meant, it actually drove me closer back to, for me, the at-large representation for school committee.

156
00:14:24,401 --> 00:14:31,463
So I don't quite know just anybody, maybe I could just ask you your opinions of where you're sitting.

157
00:14:32,743 --> 00:14:34,603
Can I nudge you a little bit on that, Paulette?

158
00:14:35,003 --> 00:14:35,203
Sure.

159
00:14:35,663 --> 00:14:41,125
What made you lean now more solidly toward at large?

160
00:14:41,545 --> 00:14:43,385
What about that?

161
00:14:43,905 --> 00:14:51,147
What was the, or what was a factor that led you back to being more solidly

162
00:14:52,853 --> 00:14:54,574
leaning toward at large.

163
00:14:55,095 --> 00:15:06,761
Because I know that in this past election cycle, I know that school committee members went out and tried to talk up being on the school committee.

164
00:15:07,462 --> 00:15:10,824
They were encouraging people to run for school committee.

165
00:15:11,544 --> 00:15:16,229
In the past, we have encouraged people to run for school committee.

166
00:15:17,110 --> 00:15:17,410
Okay?

167
00:15:17,470 --> 00:15:20,013
We haven't sort of sat there and said, no, we don't want competition.

168
00:15:20,253 --> 00:15:20,994
It's the opposite.

169
00:15:21,034 --> 00:15:21,875
That's the funny thing.

170
00:15:22,775 --> 00:15:25,278
We wanted more people to run for school committee.

171
00:15:25,798 --> 00:15:34,507
And it wasn't like, you know, people who tend to

172
00:15:35,992 --> 00:15:42,355
run for school committee by and large are people who either have kids or have a particular interest in education.

173
00:15:44,116 --> 00:15:49,938
It may have people who have had kids, but they have particular interest in education one way or the other.

174
00:15:49,958 --> 00:15:54,300
And while when you run for city council,

175
00:15:56,931 --> 00:15:59,853
The difference is that you're more interested in the workings of the city.

176
00:16:00,174 --> 00:16:03,597
There's more things that touch you specifically.

177
00:16:03,677 --> 00:16:09,562
So there's always been more candidates for city council than there has been for school committee.

178
00:16:13,205 --> 00:16:16,846
And by the way, you know, I absolutely have argued with this with myself so many times.

179
00:16:17,606 --> 00:16:23,247
I absolutely see some virtue in having a ward.

180
00:16:23,367 --> 00:16:39,791
And if I were to, I mean, my perfect is say, okay, let's combine wards to make four ward representation and then have two at large plus the mayor.

181
00:16:41,288 --> 00:16:43,048
Okay, can I can I ask you a question?

182
00:16:43,149 --> 00:16:46,309
Are you in favor of ward representation for the city council?

183
00:16:47,530 --> 00:16:51,531
Um, I know that many others are.

184
00:16:51,551 --> 00:17:00,113
And because of that, I am comfortable enough with it to say, Okay, yeah, I see.

185
00:17:00,753 --> 00:17:02,193
I see a difference in their roles.

186
00:17:03,074 --> 00:17:04,194
Okay.

187
00:17:04,882 --> 00:17:05,182
Okay.

188
00:17:05,262 --> 00:17:12,267
And I totally get, I mean, I listened to the teacher from the Curtis Tufts and she said, well, actually I might've liked having someone.

189
00:17:12,628 --> 00:17:16,911
And part of me said, damn, sorry.

190
00:17:17,451 --> 00:17:22,635
I failed her because she didn't understand I was interested in the Curtis Tufts.

191
00:17:23,235 --> 00:17:30,601
But frankly, one of my colleagues, Erin, was very interested in the Curtis Tufts and took a major role in the Curtis Tufts.

192
00:17:30,861 --> 00:17:33,343
So frankly, I could spend some energy elsewhere.

193
00:17:34,320 --> 00:17:39,502
You don't need all of the school committee members interested in the same thing all the time.

194
00:17:39,722 --> 00:17:42,603
It's better if you find your Kathy Kretz.

195
00:17:42,904 --> 00:17:44,604
She was great with the vocational school.

196
00:17:45,164 --> 00:17:45,645
Wonderful.

197
00:17:46,005 --> 00:17:47,645
You each had your niche.

198
00:17:47,665 --> 00:17:47,826
Right.

199
00:17:48,066 --> 00:17:49,106
You have your niche.

200
00:17:49,466 --> 00:17:50,527
You have a role you play.

201
00:17:50,907 --> 00:17:51,947
And the role changed.

202
00:17:52,007 --> 00:17:53,488
Clearly, the role changed for me.

203
00:17:53,908 --> 00:17:57,129
I once had the youngest kids and the only kids.

204
00:17:57,209 --> 00:17:58,310
I had the only kids.

205
00:18:00,213 --> 00:18:09,546
As a member of the school committee, but that changed over time and then all of a sudden I got old and known, lo and behold, everybody else had kids and I didn't, you know, so.

206
00:18:12,205 --> 00:18:18,367
Anyway, so this has obviously been, it's very, very difficult for me.

207
00:18:19,367 --> 00:18:27,890
The strongest thing I personally feel is having the mayor as head of the school committee.

208
00:18:28,670 --> 00:18:35,933
Absolutely having the mayor on it with a preference for having the mayor as the head.

209
00:18:37,292 --> 00:18:41,857
I agree that the mayor should be on it, but I'm still not decided whether I think the mayor should be chair or not.

210
00:18:43,438 --> 00:18:43,919
Yeah, I know.

211
00:18:44,660 --> 00:18:44,840
Yeah.

212
00:18:45,721 --> 00:18:56,552
So, Eunice and Ron, I kind of hear you saying, and some of the things that you've said, which are really important to me, is keep it simple.

213
00:18:58,011 --> 00:19:08,804
Let me just say that, you know, the last while you guys were having the last meeting and I was sitting in the dark, I spent a lot of time thinking about what occurred at our last meeting when the citizens were speaking up.

214
00:19:08,884 --> 00:19:14,410
So my opinions are usually strong and.

215
00:19:16,175 --> 00:19:20,816
usually unwaving, and usually, you know, I think I've done enough research to understand it.

216
00:19:20,836 --> 00:19:26,977
So let me just, I'll just go and give you my opinion of where I think I would like to see it going.

217
00:19:28,237 --> 00:19:42,840
I strongly believe, after listening to the folks who contributed to our meeting two weeks ago, that the ward representation piece doesn't differ from city council to school committee.

218
00:19:43,963 --> 00:19:48,508
It gives representation to each of the wards.

219
00:19:48,549 --> 00:19:58,941
And I think that's a very essential piece to when we don't know who is in each ward, let's assume they're all blank and we're writing something for 50 years down the road.

220
00:20:00,221 --> 00:20:11,546
I think it definitely follows the policy where folks in a neighborhood realize that someone in that neighborhood is on the school committee and on the city council.

221
00:20:11,666 --> 00:20:15,228
Secondly, I know there's been a lot of talk about elections.

222
00:20:16,408 --> 00:20:19,070
This piece is a very easy piece because

223
00:20:20,123 --> 00:20:28,928
Elections, number one, under this ward representation piece, you only have to campaign to one-eighth of the city.

224
00:20:29,548 --> 00:20:30,689
So your costs are lower.

225
00:20:31,209 --> 00:20:32,930
Your time involvement is lower.

226
00:20:33,430 --> 00:20:42,335
And hopefully, if you're doing the good job of a school committee person, your ward knows you and knows whether they want you to continue.

227
00:20:42,855 --> 00:20:48,198
So I think that all the complications of two years, every two years, I've got to run a campaign.

228
00:20:48,938 --> 00:20:59,383
I just don't, I think under the ward representation piece, I think that if the school committee person is doing the job, they're communicating back and forth, there's no campaigning.

229
00:20:59,484 --> 00:21:02,625
I know Sally or Jimmy is the school committee person.

230
00:21:03,025 --> 00:21:05,006
I like them because of this, I like them because of that.

231
00:21:05,507 --> 00:21:15,512
So I think the two-year piece is kind of a moot point when you're narrowing down the size of the campaign.

232
00:21:16,428 --> 00:21:27,462
I also think that two years is the right amount of time, because as we see, it's a very challenging task to be in the school committee, even with the little raise they just got.

233
00:21:27,662 --> 00:21:29,404
It's very involved.

234
00:21:32,702 --> 00:21:53,038
And to that point, going from seven to nine school committee men and women, if we're talking about eight wards and one mayor, I also think that we should look at, and Paulette, you can speak to this too, is if I have six school committee men in the ward and the mayor,

235
00:21:53,819 --> 00:21:55,600
versus eight and the mayor.

236
00:21:55,721 --> 00:22:12,714
I have an opportunity to have more people working on those committees and lowering the workload or giving the ability to create new and better plans going in the future, as opposed to being bogged down in a committee that I may or may not love, but I know it has to be done.

237
00:22:13,174 --> 00:22:15,016
So I think when you add

238
00:22:15,456 --> 00:22:25,304
representation on a school committee, you're also adding bodies that can handle the roles of subcommittee leaders, which is a major part of what they do.

239
00:22:26,525 --> 00:22:29,707
So I think there's a lot of benefits to going to 8-1.

240
00:22:30,288 --> 00:22:37,173
I think the mayor must be on the school committee, but not in the role of chairperson.

241
00:22:37,773 --> 00:22:40,896
I think the chairperson has a high function

242
00:22:42,537 --> 00:22:46,619
functional job to get the school committee to stay on board.

243
00:22:47,239 --> 00:22:49,520
The mayor does not have to be the chairperson.

244
00:22:49,660 --> 00:22:54,062
He or she is still the mayor on the school committee.

245
00:22:54,502 --> 00:23:01,205
So policies, procedures, commitment to those ultimately are the responsibility of the mayor.

246
00:23:01,585 --> 00:23:04,487
So that doesn't get lost because the mayor is on the committee.

247
00:23:05,047 --> 00:23:09,489
What does get lost is the mayor using up

248
00:23:12,589 --> 00:23:16,070
running a meeting, it's just not simple, as we know from running these subcommittee meetings.

249
00:23:16,710 --> 00:23:23,771
To run these meetings, I think it would be refreshing to have somebody else doing it, but the mayor, obviously, I strongly believe should be on the committee.

250
00:23:24,071 --> 00:23:26,011
Brian, just one thing.

251
00:23:26,371 --> 00:23:27,392
Sure.

252
00:23:27,432 --> 00:23:30,352
We talked to our current mayor specifically about this.

253
00:23:31,332 --> 00:23:32,212
There is a funny thing.

254
00:23:32,813 --> 00:23:41,034
As the vice chair, I was called upon to run the meetings of the school committee whenever the mayor couldn't be there.

255
00:23:41,658 --> 00:23:42,018
Okay.

256
00:23:42,058 --> 00:23:42,258
Right.

257
00:23:42,518 --> 00:23:42,758
Yeah.

258
00:23:43,619 --> 00:23:48,181
When you're running the meeting, you get to listen to everybody.

259
00:23:48,961 --> 00:23:56,184
When you are a member, you are preparing what you're going to say and being ready to say.

260
00:23:56,844 --> 00:23:57,685
If you notice,

261
00:23:58,727 --> 00:24:12,647
Often, the mayor actually doesn't chime in until the end or summation piece and not necessarily as much as the other meeting so they're being in it is just a little bit different than what you might.

262
00:24:14,393 --> 00:24:16,694
And I have no experience in the school committee world.

263
00:24:16,814 --> 00:24:28,356
I just didn't know that the chairman of a school committee is also the person behind the scenes who sets agenda, sets procedure, the path that they're going on.

264
00:24:28,996 --> 00:24:35,717
And we also have a superintendent who sits in the committee who is not a committee member.

265
00:24:36,257 --> 00:24:40,538
And I think that she does an excellent job of her role as being the superintendent.

266
00:24:40,558 --> 00:24:42,078
And I don't see why the mayor can't

267
00:24:43,457 --> 00:24:44,538
have that role, too.

268
00:24:45,699 --> 00:24:46,380
That's the mayor.

269
00:24:46,620 --> 00:24:47,440
The mayor is there.

270
00:24:47,741 --> 00:24:51,664
The mayor will answer those questions if they come up in a committee meeting.

271
00:24:52,225 --> 00:24:53,225
I'm just not sure.

272
00:24:53,245 --> 00:24:57,389
The mayor, I believe, is the ultimate responsibility for everything in the city.

273
00:24:57,629 --> 00:24:58,770
It's the CEO job.

274
00:24:59,431 --> 00:25:07,357
But I also think that we heard from a lot of school committee people who suggested that they would like

275
00:25:08,412 --> 00:25:10,013
to have the mayor not be the chairperson.

276
00:25:10,253 --> 00:25:15,718
But we also heard from the other half of the school committee, quite honestly, I think it's pretty well split.

277
00:25:16,360 --> 00:25:19,623
Yeah, yeah, yeah, no, no, I'm listening and I'm weighing what I heard.

278
00:25:20,003 --> 00:25:29,932
And I also know that the amount of money that we're making does not give us, you know, this is way above our pay grade, but it is our job to make this.

279
00:25:29,972 --> 00:25:31,613
Wait, what amount of money is that, Ron?

280
00:25:31,653 --> 00:25:33,135
Yeah, what are you talking about?

281
00:25:33,155 --> 00:25:34,796
Money, there's no money.

282
00:25:34,836 --> 00:25:35,537
Free Zoom.

283
00:25:35,577 --> 00:25:36,578
Free Zoom.

284
00:25:37,038 --> 00:25:38,479
Who now thinks we're getting paid.

285
00:25:38,539 --> 00:25:42,543
What I'm saying, if anybody lives in the city, they know that's not true.

286
00:25:45,061 --> 00:25:48,323
My point is that our job is to make a choice here.

287
00:25:48,583 --> 00:25:54,205
So I've made my choice based on the input of school committee.

288
00:25:54,766 --> 00:26:00,469
I've also, I know the mayor of Malden says he doesn't think he should be on the school committee.

289
00:26:00,909 --> 00:26:04,010
So there's, everybody has an opinion.

290
00:26:04,571 --> 00:26:06,652
We have to take those opinions,

291
00:26:07,732 --> 00:26:09,914
and come up with a recommendation and a vote.

292
00:26:09,974 --> 00:26:15,037
And if you ask for my opinion, these are my opinions.

293
00:26:15,358 --> 00:26:20,101
I think Ward matches and mirrors what we're trying to do at the city council.

294
00:26:20,661 --> 00:26:29,447
And I think the citizens who spoke at our meeting two meetings ago echoed that sentiment that they want that kind of representation.

295
00:26:29,587 --> 00:26:30,408
So that's what I heard.

296
00:26:31,174 --> 00:26:41,221
I think the thing that we have in common that I've heard so far is we all agree the mayor should at least be on the school committee.

297
00:26:42,742 --> 00:26:44,063
So we have something in common.

298
00:26:44,263 --> 00:26:45,924
Yay.

299
00:26:46,024 --> 00:26:47,445
All right, motion to adjourn.

300
00:26:49,986 --> 00:26:52,548
I would like to say this.

301
00:26:53,128 --> 00:27:00,073
Ron, you just brought up a very important point that I hadn't really been intentional in thinking about.

302
00:27:00,829 --> 00:27:13,186
When you talked about the eight members of the school committee, you know, I think the distribution of committee work is something that's much more doable when you have that number of people.

303
00:27:13,306 --> 00:27:18,013
I think that's a point that I hadn't really kind of honed in on.

304
00:27:18,703 --> 00:27:22,225
So I appreciate your bringing that forth.

305
00:27:22,285 --> 00:27:24,746
That's really caused me to do a little bit more thinking.

306
00:27:25,446 --> 00:27:27,127
And I just want to know the opposite of that.

307
00:27:27,807 --> 00:27:28,687
No, not just yet.

308
00:27:28,707 --> 00:27:29,287
I want to finish.

309
00:27:29,307 --> 00:27:36,770
Yeah, I just want to know that that's OK.

310
00:27:38,431 --> 00:27:46,554
I have a real concern myself about the amount of the term for the school committee members.

311
00:27:47,335 --> 00:27:47,615
Well,

312
00:27:48,762 --> 00:27:56,584
To be, I think we're trying to come up with from what we hear from the public, what we read about other towns, what we hear from other mayors, school committee members.

313
00:27:57,324 --> 00:28:00,725
And Paulette is a great person for us to have because she's actually been there.

314
00:28:02,065 --> 00:28:05,686
But I think that two years is too short.

315
00:28:06,446 --> 00:28:08,466
I think you get in, you're getting out.

316
00:28:09,007 --> 00:28:10,847
You're getting in, you're running for re-election.

317
00:28:11,442 --> 00:28:19,728
I think for me, it would have to be, I think the most efficient and effective way would be minimum three years, minimum three.

318
00:28:20,429 --> 00:28:28,895
And I know that you talked, another point that Ron brought up was if we do it in wards, it's not as costly to run elections again.

319
00:28:28,995 --> 00:28:35,439
So in my case, that would be a plus for whether we, you know, it would be three years or two years and my vote would be three.

320
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:40,403
So Paulette, the other side of what you wanted to say, I just wanted to get that out before I lost my train of thought.

321
00:28:41,297 --> 00:28:56,425
Oh, the other side is what you wanted to say, is in the way that we worked, every committee member was responsible for a committee, and other committee members were members of it.

322
00:28:56,966 --> 00:28:58,607
So we typically had three.

323
00:28:59,107 --> 00:29:09,573
So if you add more committees, it means that there will be other more places where you'd also have to be too.

324
00:29:10,413 --> 00:29:17,156
But anyway, so it's a- We could get more done.

325
00:29:18,656 --> 00:29:33,122
Paulette, talking about the committee structure that you were talking about, and I know that you've mentioned that there was a whole lot of committee work when you were on there and a lot of hours and things like that.

326
00:29:33,142 --> 00:29:38,624
I sense that they have changed their committee structure so that,

327
00:29:40,958 --> 00:29:46,124
I, you know, I, I think they have about a half a dozen or so committees and they only.

328
00:29:47,218 --> 00:29:54,140
begin to work when something from the entire body is a paper is referred to that committee.

329
00:29:54,200 --> 00:29:59,862
So they don't go off and start each committee doesn't, you know, like start a project of their own.

330
00:30:00,243 --> 00:30:03,364
They have to wait for something to be referred to them.

331
00:30:03,644 --> 00:30:06,085
And then they begin to meet on that.

332
00:30:06,205 --> 00:30:14,047
I've gotten the sense in the last, since they instituted that rule, um, which was maybe, I don't know, a year and a half ago, two years ago, um,

333
00:30:16,387 --> 00:30:19,389
I get the sense that they don't meet much.

334
00:30:19,590 --> 00:30:21,111
Some of the committees don't meet at all.

335
00:30:21,611 --> 00:30:23,533
So Eunice, you're absolutely right.

336
00:30:23,733 --> 00:30:37,223
And it has changed over time to more complicated, less complicated, more complicated, less complicated, somewhat depending on who the members are and who the superintendent was.

337
00:30:37,344 --> 00:30:39,805
I mean, there was a point where it was absolutely

338
00:30:41,327 --> 00:30:43,188
It burned everybody out, quite honestly.

339
00:30:43,208 --> 00:30:50,033
I think that there is a shift now, which is the way it really ought to be, is that something's referred from the committee.

340
00:30:50,053 --> 00:30:53,256
Which is the way it works on city council, too.

341
00:30:53,316 --> 00:31:00,641
I'm really looking to try and see where our commonalities are, where we're in agreement.

342
00:31:02,970 --> 00:31:18,380
You know, I do feel if we suggest ward representation, we are gonna have to be so clear about what happens if there's not a candidate from that ward or if the candidate steps down and there's no one, you know, then does it go to a net large?

343
00:31:18,721 --> 00:31:29,348
So we really have to hypothetically, if that's what we're gonna recommend, we have to be so clear on the potential fallout from that.

344
00:31:30,163 --> 00:31:32,085
I'll add just a point of information.

345
00:31:33,166 --> 00:31:42,734
We did look at when a ward cannot produce a candidate, and it kind of scrolls all the way down to where it says you must find a candidate.

346
00:31:43,194 --> 00:31:46,757
So it's interesting that there are no rules, and we should have.

347
00:31:46,857 --> 00:31:50,120
And while Milva has arrived, I want to ask another point of information.

348
00:31:50,800 --> 00:32:03,187
I remember vaguely last meeting we talked about three-year term being a nightmare or for some reason, and I just want to get that out before we start entertaining two versus three versus four.

349
00:32:03,207 --> 00:32:09,210
I know Milva had mentioned it, and I honestly don't remember what it was, but that's what I recall.

350
00:32:09,290 --> 00:32:13,953
So maybe Milva can just update us to get that portion of the three-year piece out.

351
00:32:14,802 --> 00:32:33,610
Sure, the three-year terms present, they could present difficulties for the elections department because you would inevitably have to have local elections on years when the state and the federal government had elections.

352
00:32:35,946 --> 00:32:38,568
they can't be on the same ballot.

353
00:32:39,989 --> 00:32:55,978
So you would have voters, you would have the elections department having to figure out how to navigate that, basically, how to navigate having two ballots, having some people coming to the polls who were going to vote in both elections, some people only voting in one election.

354
00:32:55,998 --> 00:32:58,599
They would have to figure out how to navigate that.

355
00:33:01,165 --> 00:33:09,247
And it's just not, there are not really many cities that try to do that because of that.

356
00:33:10,288 --> 00:33:25,792
And towns will have elections maybe on off years or on years, same year as the state or federal, but they have elections, they can have elections in the spring and cities don't do that, so.

357
00:33:28,624 --> 00:33:29,845
Doesn't mean it's impossible.

358
00:33:29,865 --> 00:33:32,026
It's just, it's not easy.

359
00:33:32,706 --> 00:33:34,186
Yeah.

360
00:33:34,907 --> 00:33:38,568
If I may toss in my two cents and then some.

361
00:33:41,150 --> 00:33:43,891
So, well, let's see a few things.

362
00:33:44,071 --> 00:33:48,773
The term length, I think four is,

363
00:33:51,425 --> 00:33:55,227
I think four is too long, although I see what the superintendent's saying.

364
00:33:55,267 --> 00:34:01,170
I think three years is definitely the sweet spot if we can find a way to make it work.

365
00:34:02,610 --> 00:34:08,093
Regarding ward representation, I thought in Cheryl's response,

366
00:34:09,313 --> 00:34:18,342
To the questionnaire, Cheryl Rodriguez, I thought she had a really interesting point about words may lessen that we all have.

367
00:34:18,542 --> 00:34:23,888
We have to all vote to appease the one school that has the largest amount of voters living in its boundaries.

368
00:34:24,088 --> 00:34:26,230
Other schools deserve a voice too.

369
00:34:27,511 --> 00:34:36,062
Far too long that has largely been impossible because those that vote get the most attention quote unquote from candidate Cheryl Rodriguez.

370
00:34:37,424 --> 00:34:44,293
I thought that was interesting because if you actually look at the makeup, the current makeup of the school committee, I think.

371
00:34:46,762 --> 00:34:55,472
Is it four out of the six, not counting the mayor, come from the same ward, which is where the Brooks School is?

372
00:34:56,874 --> 00:35:00,698
And I think that that's been the case in other cases.

373
00:35:01,239 --> 00:35:05,784
So I think ward representation would ensure that all schools

374
00:35:08,334 --> 00:35:26,324
have somebody, even though the at-large, everybody is supposed to be everybody's voice, I think having somebody that lives in your area, in your ward, whose kids might go to that neighborhood school, I think that there would be a benefit to that.

375
00:35:26,444 --> 00:35:33,788
So I think that that's a positive for ward representation on the school committee.

376
00:35:35,269 --> 00:35:36,349
As far as the mayor,

377
00:35:39,102 --> 00:35:42,623
for me on the school committee, but not the chair.

378
00:35:42,643 --> 00:36:00,649
And my reasons or thoughts that is, I think the mayor brings to the school committee, the budget knowledge and the knowledge of the entire city and how all the moving pieces and parts interact together.

379
00:36:00,789 --> 00:36:03,529
So I think her presence there is important.

380
00:36:05,190 --> 00:36:07,951
But I think being the chair,

381
00:36:09,428 --> 00:36:13,270
means she's agenda setting, she's organizing.

382
00:36:13,290 --> 00:36:19,833
On top of all of the other responsibilities of her job, I think that needs to go to somebody else.

383
00:36:20,874 --> 00:36:29,137
So she's not burdened with all of the logistical housekeeping aspects of being the chair.

384
00:36:31,745 --> 00:36:45,310
Could we, I see that some other communities have the mayor on there and she's either a non-voting member or she's voting only in a tiebreaker situation.

385
00:36:45,330 --> 00:36:51,772
That could be something to consider as well.

386
00:36:53,993 --> 00:36:54,733
And I wonder,

387
00:36:56,524 --> 00:37:02,107
In two ways, does she have undue influence as the chair, as she's the mayor?

388
00:37:03,048 --> 00:37:10,392
And in some cases where we have controversial subjects, how she votes.

389
00:37:14,262 --> 00:37:17,146
is sort of an optics thing as well.

390
00:37:17,807 --> 00:37:20,431
So Eunice, can I just make one point here?

391
00:37:20,771 --> 00:37:21,052
Sure.

392
00:37:21,632 --> 00:37:25,458
You're looking at it as, does she have undue influence?

393
00:37:26,239 --> 00:37:30,264
And I am looking at it as, when she's there,

394
00:37:32,037 --> 00:37:42,325
I and being the head for me means she or he puts more pressure on them to be there much more frequently than just being a member.

395
00:37:42,765 --> 00:37:47,148
OK, that it's not does she have undue influence?

396
00:37:47,569 --> 00:37:52,592
It's do the other school committee members get to make sure?

397
00:37:52,612 --> 00:38:00,258
I mean, that's the value of having her or him as the chair is or them as

398
00:38:01,809 --> 00:38:07,013
is that I'm able to influence her, not her influencing the committee.

399
00:38:07,313 --> 00:38:12,316
So just a different perspective, again, from having been a member.

400
00:38:12,336 --> 00:38:26,806
That's why I wanted the mayor there, because that was my opportunity to really make my case and for every other school committee members to make their case to the mayor.

401
00:38:27,086 --> 00:38:28,106
And it was powerful.

402
00:38:30,088 --> 00:38:37,512
Anyway, I'm again looking to say, how do we want to proceed?

403
00:38:38,093 --> 00:38:38,573
Oh, I see.

404
00:38:38,833 --> 00:38:39,053
Sorry.

405
00:38:39,073 --> 00:38:43,096
I'm going to take, I see Bill has his hand up.

406
00:38:43,136 --> 00:38:44,897
So Bill, I recognize you.

407
00:38:46,938 --> 00:38:48,158
Please unmute yourself, Bill.

408
00:38:49,739 --> 00:38:50,280
OK, I'm sorry.

409
00:38:50,500 --> 00:38:53,121
I always get confused when I start scrambling around.

410
00:38:53,501 --> 00:38:55,643
So I'm just trying to think outside the box.

411
00:38:55,683 --> 00:38:59,185
And this could be completely dumb or completely not even capable.

412
00:39:00,221 --> 00:39:18,804
do other cities by any chance like you know you have your basic school committee and then within those school committees you know you have your uh subcommittee uh meetings and one chairs it and you might have another two that are on there correct yes that's normally how it goes but is there any city like that does let's just say one one person chairs it and then and then from

413
00:39:19,565 --> 00:39:21,926
the city, you get volunteers.

414
00:39:21,986 --> 00:39:27,868
Sort of how the city does now with, let's just say, the veterans or how they have people volunteer.

415
00:39:27,888 --> 00:39:36,450
And then that way, a few people maybe do a lot of the work and report back to whoever the committee, the head person is to that subcommittee.

416
00:39:36,491 --> 00:39:38,291
And then would that help lessen the load?

417
00:39:38,311 --> 00:39:40,932
Or is that something that would not even be able to be done?

418
00:39:40,952 --> 00:39:42,312
Do you know what I'm saying?

419
00:39:42,733 --> 00:39:44,793
Yes, I do understand what you're saying, Bill.

420
00:39:45,213 --> 00:39:46,314
I honestly don't know.

421
00:39:48,374 --> 00:39:48,694
I don't.

422
00:39:51,337 --> 00:40:00,706
And with that, maybe even bring in more potential candidates in the long run if they say, you know, I might sort of like this if they just sort of get getting their feet wet and that might get somebody to even run for the position.

423
00:40:01,126 --> 00:40:05,411
There certainly has been a time when we have sought other.

424
00:40:06,772 --> 00:40:09,534
citizen participation, and that was at budget time.

425
00:40:10,315 --> 00:40:23,746
And for a while, each school committee member invited, chose someone from the public to be their person, if you would, who attended all the budget committees with meetings with them.

426
00:40:24,246 --> 00:40:31,913
And often it was people who had demonstrated interest in being on the school committee, and it really gave them a chance to see what it was like.

427
00:40:32,993 --> 00:40:36,374
Some went on to run for school committee and some did not because they said, oh, my God.

428
00:40:36,394 --> 00:40:37,054
Yeah.

429
00:40:37,654 --> 00:40:45,576
So but I was just wondering if it like, you know, lessens the load, because like some of them are on maybe two or three committees.

430
00:40:45,616 --> 00:40:46,216
You know what I mean?

431
00:40:46,416 --> 00:40:48,577
Whether they share one or if they're just on it.

432
00:40:48,997 --> 00:40:56,319
But maybe if if each one just shares one and you know, if you had if you had a couple of volunteers, you know, obviously they'd have to be volunteers.

433
00:40:56,379 --> 00:41:01,240
And then they just you know, they just sort of just report to whoever the chair is of that subcommittee.

434
00:41:01,480 --> 00:41:03,441
I'm just I'm just thinking if that can be done at all.

435
00:41:03,781 --> 00:41:05,342
I understand exactly what you're saying.

436
00:41:05,402 --> 00:41:12,826
I will tell you that my experience is and you may remember this happening as well from your days is that.

437
00:41:13,546 --> 00:41:17,488
So let's say it was a committee on buildings and grounds.

438
00:41:17,988 --> 00:41:21,670
OK, so interesting topic, important topic.

439
00:41:22,251 --> 00:41:23,952
Well, the two voting members go.

440
00:41:25,032 --> 00:41:28,795
But so do two or three other members who are just so interested in the topic.

441
00:41:29,175 --> 00:41:39,322
And while they are not a voting member of the subcommittee, what really happens is that more than two, more than the members of the committee itself used to go.

442
00:41:39,882 --> 00:41:40,563
Now, again,

443
00:41:41,003 --> 00:41:47,647
Remember, we went through some years where, especially the COVID years, it was crazy times and everybody showed up for everything.

444
00:41:47,687 --> 00:41:49,268
It was a lot of meetings and whatever.

445
00:41:49,788 --> 00:42:06,578
Now, I think that after going through a very intense time of so many meetings where people were generating their own topics all the time, I think it has backed off a little bit so that it makes more sense and people have their committee that they're ahead of.

446
00:42:08,500 --> 00:42:10,901
You know, they're responsive to whatever comes up.

447
00:42:11,641 --> 00:42:17,125
And part of that, of course, is that they're talking to the superintendent and saying, you know, this is an important issue.

448
00:42:17,145 --> 00:42:22,728
So I don't think we need to get that caught up in that in the workload of the committee.

449
00:42:22,748 --> 00:42:34,615
I think we need to, I would not necessarily have the mayor be the head of a committee, additional head of a committee.

450
00:42:34,836 --> 00:42:36,657
So as we think about writing these things,

451
00:42:37,657 --> 00:42:45,001
I am hearing generally more preference for ward than at large.

452
00:42:45,322 --> 00:42:49,764
But Bill, why don't you just, I don't mean to cut you off if you've got anything else you want to add.

453
00:42:49,824 --> 00:42:51,905
No, that's all I had to add.

454
00:42:51,925 --> 00:42:56,948
I was just very curious of it, not even really suggesting it, just throwing it out there.

455
00:42:57,188 --> 00:42:57,509
That's all.

456
00:42:57,609 --> 00:42:57,889
Okay.

457
00:42:58,309 --> 00:42:58,829
Thank you, Bill.

458
00:42:59,009 --> 00:42:59,330
Thank you.

459
00:42:59,770 --> 00:42:59,870
Yep.

460
00:43:02,530 --> 00:43:04,090
Paulette, can I ask you a question?

461
00:43:04,110 --> 00:43:05,771
Sure.

462
00:43:05,871 --> 00:43:08,291
I defer to you for experience on the school committee.

463
00:43:08,831 --> 00:43:13,732
That's why, you know, your value to this committee is very important.

464
00:43:15,053 --> 00:43:25,395
Reading some of the school committee, active school committee or recently active school committee members who did not think that the mayor should be chairperson,

465
00:43:27,667 --> 00:43:37,136
We're talking about not having a great pool, a multiple pool of choices and campaigns to school committee person.

466
00:43:37,156 --> 00:43:47,225
Do you think that if the mayor was to not be the chairperson and perform more of a role as the superintendent does in those school committee meetings,

467
00:43:47,927 --> 00:44:04,005
Do you think that someone interested in the school committee would have more incentive realizing that they could potentially be the chairperson of that school committee and have the ability to be more involved in shaping and fashioning the way the school and education is in Medford?

468
00:44:09,457 --> 00:44:12,298
I don't know, because, you know, we just never did it that way.

469
00:44:12,398 --> 00:44:22,043
I think when we get to the clauses about how we elect the chair, if we're going to go for

470
00:44:23,175 --> 00:44:31,138
in that mode, I think it's very important that the chair rotates every year, a different chair every year.

471
00:44:32,279 --> 00:44:37,941
And that should be true with the secretary.

472
00:44:38,741 --> 00:44:45,084
It is a little more challenging with the secretary because one of the secretary's duties is to sign the bills.

473
00:44:45,844 --> 00:44:55,651
That means that they either need, and I don't know exactly what they're doing now because it's changed, but there is an onus of a burden of work that needs to be done.

474
00:44:56,092 --> 00:44:57,973
But that should also change.

475
00:44:59,914 --> 00:45:08,180
I remember, you know, one time I was the secretary for far too many years, and I kept on saying I shouldn't be the secretary anymore because

476
00:45:09,190 --> 00:45:12,232
other eyes needed to be on the financial stuff.

477
00:45:12,852 --> 00:45:15,073
And nobody could do it, so that's why I ended up doing it.

478
00:45:15,814 --> 00:45:31,583
But I think we need to put in our charter that those positions will rotate amongst the members, and the members themselves will select who the chair is, which is what's being done now.

479
00:45:32,783 --> 00:45:36,966
I completely agree, but I point out something.

480
00:45:37,863 --> 00:45:41,887
If the mayor is not the chair, then we have.

481
00:45:42,748 --> 00:45:46,272
On the school committee, 3 leadership roles, the chair.

482
00:45:46,952 --> 00:45:49,455
The vice chair and the secretary.

483
00:45:50,836 --> 00:45:54,600
And when we started out this term.

484
00:45:55,488 --> 00:46:23,671
you know, eight weeks ago or so, we had, and removing the mayor out of the equation for a moment, and just looking at the remaining six, back in January when they were inaugurated, we had, and going back to what I said, we have three leadership roles, we had three veteran school committee members, and three just starting out.

485
00:46:24,843 --> 00:46:33,469
Now, eight weeks in, because we have a resignation, now we're down to two veterans and four new folks.

486
00:46:34,570 --> 00:46:43,215
And that could well happen again, starting a term, if there's a considerable amount of turnover.

487
00:46:43,816 --> 00:46:53,983
So then you're giving one of these leadership roles, again, extracting the mayor out of the equation, and looking at the other six, you're giving one of these leadership roles

488
00:46:54,763 --> 00:47:00,386
perhaps or maybe more to somebody who is just starting out.

489
00:47:01,387 --> 00:47:06,009
So that's just something that I'll- Just another complication there, Eunice.

490
00:47:06,149 --> 00:47:06,649
Thank you.

491
00:47:06,950 --> 00:47:09,151
Hey, that's what I'm here for.

492
00:47:09,171 --> 00:47:09,271
Right.

493
00:47:10,632 --> 00:47:15,694
But it might just speak to some stability of having the mayor as the chairperson.

494
00:47:15,935 --> 00:47:22,078
That might provide some stability given the situations the committee might find itself in.

495
00:47:22,863 --> 00:47:30,224
it would be, I think, far too challenging for a newly elected school committee member to have to take on one of those roles.

496
00:47:31,225 --> 00:47:32,885
But yet we do that in the city council.

497
00:47:33,425 --> 00:47:33,625
Right.

498
00:47:33,725 --> 00:47:33,985
I know.

499
00:47:34,005 --> 00:47:35,485
I understand that.

500
00:47:35,566 --> 00:47:36,486
And that's fine.

501
00:47:36,546 --> 00:47:38,066
We're talking about the school committee here.

502
00:47:38,086 --> 00:47:48,008
And that point, I think, is really, you know, I think that's a very interesting point that Eunice has brought forth.

503
00:47:48,952 --> 00:47:49,633
It is interesting.

504
00:47:49,674 --> 00:47:55,845
I just want to throw out whenever there's a new mayor, then you have the same situation.

505
00:47:55,865 --> 00:47:56,386
That's all.

506
00:47:56,586 --> 00:47:58,189
Just throwing that in.

507
00:47:58,490 --> 00:47:59,171
Thanks, Melva.

508
00:48:00,400 --> 00:48:01,421
No, but it's true.

509
00:48:02,241 --> 00:48:02,941
Yeah.

510
00:48:03,362 --> 00:48:21,411
To go back to the point of how to do this, from serving on a couple of the other subcommittees or just sitting in on them, I wasn't on the Article 2 and 3 subcommittee, but I sat in on a number of their meetings.

511
00:48:22,892 --> 00:48:27,575
And what they did was, and the reason I gave everybody this draft,

512
00:48:28,895 --> 00:48:36,957
was that they took each section, and I have too darn many papers in front of me.

513
00:48:38,138 --> 00:48:44,179
They color-coded and they went through each section.

514
00:48:44,900 --> 00:48:56,243
For example, Article 2, the legislative branch, Section 2.1 is very similar to Section 4.1, composition, terms of office, and eligibility.

515
00:48:59,838 --> 00:49:06,692
They took out all of the Medford Melrose Weymouth stuff and they took composition

516
00:49:08,117 --> 00:49:22,752
The 3 sections composition, the terms of office and the eligibility and they've color coded where anything in black ink is language that was reviewed by that subcommittee.

517
00:49:23,693 --> 00:49:28,799
Green ink was any language accepted by the full committee of the what are we 11 now?

518
00:49:30,195 --> 00:49:36,619
And then blue is language that warrants further investigation by the full committee.

519
00:49:36,719 --> 00:49:56,272
So what I would suggest, now that we've been talking about a bunch of this stuff for a while, if our little group here has come to any consensus on anything, is that we take section 4.1 and make a heading that says composition, and we

520
00:49:59,143 --> 00:50:13,015
put in as reading what the legislative group said, there'll be a city council that shall exercise the legislative powers of the city, shall consist of 11 members, each ward will have a single ward councilor, yada, yada, yada, yada.

521
00:50:13,616 --> 00:50:19,541
Terms of office, the term will be two years beginning the first Monday in January, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

522
00:50:20,101 --> 00:50:23,222
Right, Eunice, I think that's exactly where we're going.

523
00:50:23,302 --> 00:50:40,728
The only thing was that before we start that work, which is we're going to do this in another couple of sentences, I've been trying to figure out where this group of people, where they were landing, where we were at consensus and where we were at odds.

524
00:50:42,208 --> 00:50:48,050
And there's one other factor which we haven't really talked about, and that's staggered terms.

525
00:50:49,057 --> 00:50:57,483
And I did reach out to school committee members in another town, which has both three-year terms and staggered terms.

526
00:50:58,184 --> 00:51:09,832
And it was very interesting to have the discussion, because what I learned was that, first of all, they were a town, so they moved in March.

527
00:51:10,982 --> 00:51:17,227
And so it's a spring election, much easier for them to do the three year terms than us.

528
00:51:18,268 --> 00:51:27,335
But in doing the staggered terms that they do with their two year terms, they end up with an election every single year.

529
00:51:28,535 --> 00:51:32,017
Staggered terms would work for us in Medford.

530
00:51:32,237 --> 00:51:34,918
And I just want to, because people have asked me about this.

531
00:51:35,619 --> 00:51:44,583
If we were doing the four year term, because then we could have an election every two years and only part of the school committee would be elected.

532
00:51:45,323 --> 00:51:45,704
Okay.

533
00:51:46,484 --> 00:51:53,709
But to think about making it more crazy by having an election every year just doesn't make sense for me.

534
00:51:53,849 --> 00:52:03,295
So if we were thinking about four years, but I haven't heard that overall, I think a lot of people have decided four years feels just a little too long.

535
00:52:04,015 --> 00:52:06,136
OK, we all like three years.

536
00:52:06,817 --> 00:52:07,878
We all like three years.

537
00:52:09,023 --> 00:52:11,365
I've heard more for two years than for four years.

538
00:52:11,445 --> 00:52:20,193
But if we wanted to do staggered and four years, if you do four years, staggered would come into play, in my opinion.

539
00:52:20,514 --> 00:52:20,694
Right.

540
00:52:20,754 --> 00:52:22,816
For me, Paulette, it would be three or four.

541
00:52:23,276 --> 00:52:24,978
I'm not in favor of two-year terms at all.

542
00:52:25,538 --> 00:52:25,738
Okay.

543
00:52:25,758 --> 00:52:27,440
So we're still undecided about that.

544
00:52:27,980 --> 00:52:28,361
Yeah.

545
00:52:28,461 --> 00:52:30,883
I said that when I said my preference.

546
00:52:31,384 --> 00:52:31,664
Okay.

547
00:52:31,684 --> 00:52:31,844
Ron?

548
00:52:33,758 --> 00:52:36,239
Yeah, I agree with what Eunice said.

549
00:52:36,259 --> 00:52:45,022
I think that before we get to this, as you mentioned, we have to really, you know, we have to decide two years.

550
00:52:46,543 --> 00:52:48,523
Then we can build in this piece.

551
00:52:49,424 --> 00:52:52,085
And then we also have to present it to the committee of the whole.

552
00:52:52,165 --> 00:53:00,348
So we have to really, you know, drive to get the decision made amongst the five of us.

553
00:53:02,909 --> 00:53:05,111
to make a recommendation to the Committee of the Whole.

554
00:53:05,992 --> 00:53:15,238
And then you can go to work on this Article 4 piece, it's just going to be flawed in the fact that, well, which process are we looking at?

555
00:53:15,479 --> 00:53:18,481
And so I think the initial piece is to determine

556
00:53:19,118 --> 00:53:24,921
the length of term, the ward versus, and if we can accomplish that, I think that's a major accomplishment.

557
00:53:25,061 --> 00:53:38,387
Also, I think that in terms of my opinion of staggered terms and three-year terms is I think the most important thing that we watch is that we mirror elections of the mayor and the city council.

558
00:53:38,987 --> 00:53:44,310
so that we're all in unison, we're all going to the election box to vote at the same time.

559
00:53:44,350 --> 00:53:46,651
Whatever we do, we're all doing at the same time.

560
00:53:46,812 --> 00:53:52,615
And we also, as much as possible, coordinate that within the presidential federal elections.

561
00:53:52,635 --> 00:53:56,977
For me, in a three year, it doesn't happen.

562
00:53:58,640 --> 00:54:07,810
It wouldn't happen, but a four-year, you would have to establish that every four years on the presidential election timescale, that's when we would vote.

563
00:54:08,651 --> 00:54:12,795
I believe that that's very—and staggering, I think, puts that—

564
00:54:13,556 --> 00:54:21,979
thing out there that says, well, is this school committee person campaigning this year or are they working as a school committee person?

565
00:54:22,679 --> 00:54:26,600
I think everybody should be a full body going uniformly.

566
00:54:26,620 --> 00:54:27,481
That's just my opinion.

567
00:54:27,501 --> 00:54:33,242
I don't want to get too involved, but I do think I'd like to see us move towards a decision on ward

568
00:54:36,183 --> 00:54:45,405
term, limits, and whatever else we need to do, then we have in our pockets, this is how now we have to shape that into this document.

569
00:54:46,566 --> 00:54:48,546
Go ahead, Paulette.

570
00:54:49,086 --> 00:54:56,328
I think that at the very outset, I said, I understand from your position as being keep it simple.

571
00:54:57,696 --> 00:54:59,380
And I think that's what you're trying to do.

572
00:54:59,400 --> 00:55:03,129
Enacting one major change, which is the

573
00:55:06,928 --> 00:55:07,988
at large to ward.

574
00:55:08,528 --> 00:55:24,776
Now, you know, I clearly can be a dissenting opinion if the majority of everybody else is, and my feeling at this point because, you know, I certainly get the value of ward representation.

575
00:55:25,337 --> 00:55:31,100
I don't know how it's going to work for the school committee, but we can write it up and we can make sure that we've got

576
00:55:32,292 --> 00:55:46,942
We can write our document, if we're in agreement, if the majority of people are in agreement, let us write it up as ward representation, one school committee member from each ward and the mayor being a member.

577
00:55:47,102 --> 00:55:50,004
And we're not yet going to say what role the mayor is in.

578
00:55:50,727 --> 00:55:51,347
I agree with you 100%.

579
00:55:52,128 --> 00:56:02,214
I'm just saying that for us to move to our next piece, which is a lot of discussion, a lot of negotiating, a lot of details, we have to know that we don't want to keep going backwards to this.

580
00:56:03,134 --> 00:56:06,996
And we can't develop theories that say, well, on the three-year, let's write it this way.

581
00:56:07,077 --> 00:56:08,677
On the four-year, let's write it this way.

582
00:56:08,978 --> 00:56:10,158
On the two-year, let's write it.

583
00:56:10,178 --> 00:56:12,540
I just want to get to the point that we all believe that

584
00:56:13,403 --> 00:56:19,410
If we can come to an agreement, the five of us, and then we have to go to the 11 of us, and then we have to go to the whole city.

585
00:56:19,470 --> 00:56:21,512
So this is a major, this is not easy.

586
00:56:22,794 --> 00:56:26,979
My point is only that keeping it simple just simply means let's

587
00:56:29,332 --> 00:56:41,040
start tearing pieces away and throwing them away and paring it down so we have a path because we only have until October to have something down.

588
00:56:42,761 --> 00:56:48,504
I just think we need to stay focused before it gets caught up on us and see what happens.

589
00:56:49,385 --> 00:56:52,667
My reasoning for landing at the three years is

590
00:56:55,142 --> 00:57:10,372
I fully see where the superintendent is coming from with the frequent campaigning and not being able to gain any momentum in getting things done because then you're bringing in a new crop.

591
00:57:10,892 --> 00:57:13,034
So I am trying to.

592
00:57:14,339 --> 00:57:34,980
Respect that but I also feel like having people in for four years who Some people may think are not Serving them in the proper way Whereas you can it's easier to get rid of somebody who is

593
00:57:37,042 --> 00:57:42,525
You know, if you're if voters are feeling are are not doing the job.

594
00:57:42,545 --> 00:57:53,272
Then it's easier to live with them for 2 years and get rid of them after 2 years, which, you know, on the 1 hand is something that I prefer.

595
00:57:53,992 --> 00:57:59,335
So, and which is why I went that direction on the city council side.

596
00:57:59,355 --> 00:57:59,395
So.

597
00:58:02,788 --> 00:58:10,874
landing at three seemed to be, you know, kind of, it's I think the sweet spot for a lot of people.

598
00:58:11,014 --> 00:58:19,701
And I think it's just sort of in swirling around in my head, you know, voting my conscience is

599
00:58:21,403 --> 00:58:23,444
where I land is the best compromise.

600
00:58:23,845 --> 00:58:31,371
I don't want four because I don't want people sitting in there that I don't think are serving us well.

601
00:58:33,452 --> 00:58:38,837
But the superintendent wants four and two isn't working for her.

602
00:58:39,477 --> 00:58:41,779
So let's plop down at three.

603
00:58:43,878 --> 00:58:45,018
Can I just make a comment?

604
00:58:45,598 --> 00:58:45,838
Yeah.

605
00:58:46,198 --> 00:59:00,861
I think if you're seriously considering three years, I would suggest finding a city that has three-year terms and seeing how they work it with November elections.

606
00:59:00,881 --> 00:59:04,022
Okay.

607
00:59:04,042 --> 00:59:06,302
Did the ballot center give us a recommendation?

608
00:59:06,322 --> 00:59:11,143
They were not able to provide one.

609
00:59:11,163 --> 00:59:12,363
I couldn't find one.

610
00:59:13,108 --> 00:59:26,321
There may be one, but the only one that may, you know, Taunton may, maybe look like they might do it, but I'm not sure if their elections are in November or not.

611
00:59:26,462 --> 00:59:26,882
I don't know.

612
00:59:26,902 --> 00:59:33,589
You know, one of the things I've been thinking about as everyone's talking is I think that overall, I think what we're trying to

613
00:59:35,217 --> 00:59:38,098
get to is how can we have the best participation?

614
00:59:38,858 --> 00:59:41,439
How can we engage more people in this?

615
00:59:42,299 --> 00:59:50,022
Ron brings up some good points that if we keep it simple, which I think is a very good thing, there's certain aspects to that.

616
00:59:51,122 --> 00:59:52,983
My opinion is only my opinion.

617
00:59:53,403 --> 01:00:00,005
I believe that in this city of Method, we would do far better with at-large representation on the school committee.

618
01:00:00,759 --> 01:00:03,020
I don't see the wards participating much.

619
01:00:03,480 --> 01:00:15,123
I can tell you that from my experience of being a member of the Democratic Committee here in Medford, we have some wards where we don't even have one member in the ward, never mind a chair.

620
01:00:16,043 --> 01:00:24,305
So that's my reason for thinking that at-large would be the best way to go, whether it's city council or school committee, right?

621
01:00:25,100 --> 01:00:30,324
I think the problem with the two, three, or four years, they're all coming out.

622
01:00:31,005 --> 01:00:33,107
Four years might be too long for someone to be on it.

623
01:00:33,527 --> 01:00:36,589
What is going to be the best thing for the citizens of Medford?

624
01:00:37,810 --> 01:00:41,333
I mean, and that might be a lot to ask, but that's what I'm thinking of.

625
01:00:41,794 --> 01:00:45,297
As a citizen, how would I be more engaged in this process?

626
01:00:46,057 --> 01:00:48,499
What would make me want to be more engaged in this process?

627
01:00:50,321 --> 01:00:53,723
I think we're suffering from a lot of apathy right now.

